The paper deals with decoding algorithms for Goppa codes, which are commonly used in code-based cryptography. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes a modified version of the McEliece cryptosystem, which is a well-known code-based cryptosystem, further supporting the possibility of it belonging to cs.CR. The paper also discusses collaborative decoding, which is a technique used in error-correcting codes, indicating that it could belong to the Coding Theory (cs.CC) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of wild Goppa codes, which are a specific type of Goppa code, suggesting that it could belong to the Combinatorics (cs.CO) or Symbolic Computation (cs.SC) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the analysis of attacks on the proposed cryptosystem, which could fall under the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) or Security and Privacy (cs.SI) sub-categories.
